Let me explain: 
Cysteine/ Keratin treatment: any treatment that uses heat and chemicals does damage the hair to some extent. They should not be attempted on virgin hair or for changing hair texture just on a whiff cause they can cause permanent Damage too. However if someone has very frizzy hair this treatment may help in some controlled damage to control future breakage. 

Hair Botox is a milder form of cysteine or keratin treatment, hence damage is there but lesser so it’s a safer choice but only for the right hair type. Get reviewed by a dermatologist before you go for any such treatments.

Reverse conditioning: highly recommend this. Reverse conditioning is when you apply a conditioner or leave in product like an oil or balm before using shampoo. This helps to protect your hair cuticle which has an outer F layer made of oils. This step helps to replace this layer and clean hair without damaging it. 

Scalp oiling: been done since centuries but not proved efficient by science. Oils are meant for the hair and not for the scalp. They do not cause any hair growth and may increase dandruff too.

If oral iron isn’t doing the trick or upsets your stomach, this “Coke-lookalike” drip delivers the boost your hair follicles have been waiting for.

Ever feel like your energy (and skin) just can’t keep up anymore?
Same! As a dermatologist, I’ve started taking NAD+ IV drips — and honestly, it’s one of those inside-out shifts you can really feel.

NAD (nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide) is a molecule your body naturally makes, and it plays a major role in energy, cellular repair, and yes — even that healthy skin glow. 💧✨

Would I recommend it? Absolutely. It’s not a shortcut or a miracle fix, but if you’re looking to support your skin and body at a deeper level, it’s definitely worth exploring. Think of it as a gentle internal reset.
